sentence: Editor’s note: InvestorPlace’s Earnings Reports to Watch is updated weekly.
Please check back next week for our latest .
It was about a year ago that U.S. equity markets started to break down.
Cyclicals and retailers went first last September; the rest of the market followed roughly a month later.
The S&P 500 finished down 14% in the fourth quarter, its worst performance in seven years.
The biggest question in the short-term for investors is whether history will repeat itself.
There are signs that it will.
An e for U.S. Treasuries historically has been a warning sign for U.S. stocks.
Volatility has spiked.
Economic data has been mixed.
And with earnings season coming to an end, corporate earnings reports won’t be able to do much heavy lifting for the next six weeks.
Those reports were strong in the second quarter.
Factset Research reported that of the 90% of S&P 500 components, .
Those steady doses of good news were enough to counteract external fears.
To be sure, a lighter earnings calendar doesn’t mean markets are set to fall.
A similar dynamic held after first quarter earnings season — and markets rallied to all-time highs.
Though the calendar is somewhat light next week, there are some key earnings reports that could give clues to where the market goes from here.
A leader in a key tech sector will try and rebound after a pullback.
Beaten-down specialty retailers will look for more signs of life.
And what might be the market’s most-highly valued stock will again test investor appetites for growth and risk.
It’s a quiet week, but in this environment, still an important one.
American Eagle Outfitters (NYSE:) isn’t the biggest retailer reporting next week.
That honor goes to Lululemon Athletica (NASDAQ:), which reports on Thursday afternoon.
But Lululemon has been an outlier in the struggling specialty retail sector.
American Eagle, in contrast, clearly has been weighed down by fears surrounding the space.
Despite impressive growth from its aerie concept, AEO stock touched a 21-month low this month.
But American Eagle — and the sector — are showing some strength at the moment.
AEO stock has bounced 17% from those lows.
Shoe Carnival (NASDAQ:), Tilly’s (NYSE:) and Express (NYSE:) all posted big jumps after earnings last week.
In that context, the earnings report from American Eagle on Wednesday morning seems particularly important for both AEO and the specialty retail space.
American Eagle remains one of the largest mall-based retailers out there.
In aerie, it has one of the few concepts still opening stores.
So a strong report from American Eagle could add to the sense that the industry — including landlords like Simon Property Group (NYSE:) and Macerich (NYSE:) — can’t be written off just yet.
A miss, however, could undercut some of the optimism that’s built over the past couple of weeks.
Fiscal Q4 results from Palo Alto Networks (NYSE:) similarly look important for the company and its industry.
PANW stock faded after the Q3 report in May and now is bouncing along support around $200.
The cybersecurity sector as a whole, at least as measured by the ETFMG Prime Cyber Security ETF (NYSEARCA:), similarly is testing support after a pullback.
Given that Palo Alto is the industry leader, its report can have a knock-on effect on other stocks in the space.
Technicals aside, this looks like an important report.
Management has seen under new CEO Nikesh Arora.
There are concerns about growth (again for both Palo Alto and the industry as a whole).
A big report from Palo Alto could reaffirm that cybersecurity is an attractive long-term vertical.
A miss could suggest that growth is starting to stall out.
Even in a market where investors will pay seemingly any price for growth, Zoom Video Communications (NASDAQ:) seems to stand apart.
ZM stock trades at roughly 47x 2020 revenue estimates.
It has a $25 billion market cap on barely half a billion dollars in expected sales.
Can that valuation possibly go higher?
It wouldn’t seem like it could — but investors could have said the same thing about many growth stocks in this market.
And so the reaction to Zoom earnings, given its clear outlier status, may be more interesting than the numbers themselves.
If investors can find a way to pay even more for Zoom, that reads well to other high-multiple growth stocks in this market.
As I noted this week, trading in Salesforce.com (NYSE:) suggests valuations might finally be nearing a ceiling.
A ‘sell the news’ reaction to Zoom earnings could confirm that thesis — and raise questions about whether growth stocks on the whole at last have run too far.
As of this writing, Vince Martin has no positions in any securities mentioned.
The post appeared first on InvestorPlace.
